description: You know, when I saw this totally convinced this was a Lesser Goldfinch, but now that I'm looking it up, I am only 80% sure.  It's got the dark bill and green back, but ... and incomplete black cap.  Frustrating.  Any bird nerds want to weigh in?  My bird nerditude is insufficient.
I described this bird to someone recently as a "cardinal from hell."  Ubiquitous in the Mojave, as far as I can tell.

I decided not to bring my proper camera and telelphoto on this mini-trip to Boy Scout ... and of course saw cool birds, like this Northern Shrike (a first for me!).  Actually, there were a bunch of shrikes out that morning.  Though the mask is quite large, I think it's  a Northern and not a Loggerhead because of the very clear hook in its bill.
This is one of several cactus wrens I saw on the trip.  Cagey, but common.
Seen in Lost Palms Oasis.
This was one of two subspecies - Sceloporus occidentalis biseriatus or Sceloporus occidentalis longipes. Friends saw that it had blue scales under its chin.
Tons of the males flying around and feeding on various flowers.
Saw a few large males. Males were head-butting large barrel cacti to break off the spines and eat the fruit.

A juniper titmouse observed as part of mixed flock along with black-capped chickadees and pygmy nuthatches up high on a ridge near Pine City, JTNP.
Only 2 ungulates live in the park, and only one has blunt, rounded hooves like these.  So, definitely bighorn sheep.

Not sure about whether this is Great Horned Owl or Barn Owl.  

Those are the only 2 large owls regularly observed in the park.

Toes appear less robust than many GH Owl tracks I have seen, but its a bit difficult to tell.

Anyone else have strong evidence for one or the other?

description:
This Hammond's flycatcher was found in the scrub near the Cottonwood Spring Campground. Empids are notoriously difficult to ID. This one's identification was based on the combination of its small size, tiny, dark bill, olive back, long primaries, notched tail, and rather large-headed appearance with a small peak near the back of the crown.

This bird is on migration to its breeding grounds in the high elevation western conifer forests.

Group of 3 ewes and 3 lambs feeding on low dry vegetation.  All looked to be in great health.  Not very shy-- this was midday at a popular lookout, and they weren't far from the parking lot.  They'd startle for particularly loud car door slams, but not run.  

These are apparently part of the Little San Bernardino herd.  From the park's website: 
"Three herds live in the park
The bighorn uses open areas of low growing vegetation near rugged terrain for feeding. This habitat preference divides Joshua Tree's bighorns into three more or less separate herds. The 120 animals that live in the Eagle Mountains at the far easterm boundary of the park is the largest herd. The second consists of about 100 animals and ranges through the main part of the Little San Bernardino Mountains. The smallest herd, which numbers only 30 animals, is found in the Wonderland of Rocks. Members of this last band are the ones most often seen by park visitors."
Stiff.

description: I have several photos of a flycatcher that I have labeled ash-throated flycatcher, but I am not certain that's what the bird is. I'm not seeing much in the way of rufous coloration in the outer primaries or tail. On the other hand the bird was fairly large in size, and it was in a habitat where ash-throateds are often seen-  small canyon with a dry desert wash and scattered acacia, desert willow, and mesquite. The Aug. 10 date puts in an early fall migration time when several other flycatcher species might be moving into the area. Anyway, I'd welcome suggestions as to the ID of this bird. The general location was near the Maze Loop Trailhead. Two more photos of this bird added on Aug. 26, 2016.

description: A lazuli bunting (juvenile?) was observed in a creosote bush near the Pleasant Valley playa in Joshua Tree National Park. The first picture is mine and it's laughable as I chopped off its head, but you can see the plumage on the underparts including a warm orange-brown color as found on the lazuli bunting. The second picture is by Donna Thomas and shows some blue color in the back as well as the pattern of the wing bars. These are uncommon migrants through the Joshua Tree area. I'm open to other interpretations of this bird's ID. We didn't get the best look at it.

description: Not sure if folks can ID this based on this photo alone.  I'm posting this not for the species record, but for the behavior observed.  We watched this shrike in pursuit of a small passerine.  It chased it through the air right on front of us, then into a shrub for several seconds, then over to another shrub, and then out of sight behind a rock.  We'd never seen a shrike hunt a bird before.

description: This was in woody debris in a sandy wash along the Mastodon Peak loop. It was light brown with a clear dark brown pattern along its back. It had clear tail rings which seemed black and white at the time but don't look it in the (admittedly terrible) photos, which is why I am adding as an unidentified rattlesnake. It had taken off well in advance of my passing, so I did not see the head, and it seemed to sense when I spotted it and immediately gave me a good rattle and paused moving through the debris. I respected the warning, so the distance and speed with which it disappeared account for the remarkably poor photos.

From the Birds of North America species account: 

(1) P. nitens lepida Van Tyne, 1925. Smaller of the two subspecies: wing 86-94 mm (female), 88-96 mm (male); tail 82-95 mm (female), 86-99 mm (male) (Pyle 1997c; see also Table 3). Occupies U.S. portion of species range from California east to w. Texas (breeding records in Culberson and Jeff Davis Cos.; Oberholser 1974c) and south to s. Baja California (Cape San Lucas) and nw. Mexico (s. Sonora and Bustillos, Chihuahua; Phillips 1991). Winters south to s. Tamaulipas and central San Luis Potosí, casually to Veracruz, Guanajuato, and Aguascalientes; spreads in summer east to sw. Texas (Phillips 1991).

description: The nest was found in a 6' catclaw acacia, which is desired by this species for nesting. The hole was a small oval towards the bottom, and the twigs/dry matter made up the bulk of the nest. The nest is certainly from a verdin family, found in the Rocky Desert Scrub.

The waterfowl was small and compact. The head was black, the round body was dark gray, and the beak was white. It dove in and out of the water of the Freshwater Lake, which reflected the beautiful colors of autumn.

The passerine was small, sparrowlike, and had a bold black head, with a light beak. The body was light and pinkish brown. A flock of several of these passerine birds filled the Rocky Desert Scrub with chirping, heard from far away.

The passerine was small, sparrowlike, and had a bold black head, with a light beak. The body was light and pinkish brown. It lived among the autumn-colored willows of the thin strip of Riparian Forest.

The small passerine bird was a reserved, secretive little one. It blended in well with the undergrowth, due to its rusty brown and gray plumage. The reddish-brown tail also wagged as it hopped through the branches. This one lived in the Riparian Forest.

The large, black bird had a thick, "square" tail, thick beak, and a croak-like call that was deep, unlike the crow. It flew high above the Rocky Desert Scrub, catching the sunlight of the last rays before sunset hit.
The large, black bird had a thick, "square" tail, thick beak, and a croak-like call that was deep. It perched on top of the Joshua Tree and had a nice view of the surrounding Joshua Tree Woodland.

saw 2 or 3 of these on the same day, flat sandy habitat with some brush was the common habitat.

April 4th, 2019. 4:06pm. Mid 70’s. Small/young looking tortoise, as big as my hand. I watched it chew on dried/old/whiteish colored coyote scat. After admiring this one, I headed back on the trail, and saw another much larger tortoise, crossing the trail :) I was very lucky. This one was as big as a standard red ear slider turtle I would say, or like a teacup dish, or like my hand (I’m female). It was small. It was refreshing to see a small tortoise doing well out there :)

April 4th, 2019. Mid 70’s. 4:25pm. The picture of the same tortoise in the burrow is a little later at 6:25pm. I saw a tortoise that looked like this one back in November 2018, right exactly in this spot. I think it possibly could be the same one. Before seeing this one, I saw a smaller tortoise (as big as my hand) about 50 feet away! After admiring both tortoises, I continued my hike and on the way back, stopped to look for both tortoises and only saw the bigger one in its burrow. It was super neat to see :)

description: I came up from the Indian Cove parking area for Boy Scout Trail. Temperatures in the low-mid 70’s, breezy and then calm at times. You know those “slot canyon” areas? If you count from the first up from Indian Cove parking, this tortoise was in the third slot. I saw it around 1pm and on my way back down, I saw it’s tracks in the sand and kept walking, eyeing the tracks, and sure enough, the tortoise was still in the wash, walking and browsing at 4:55pm. When I saw it at 1pm, it was eating lupine. I’ve heard lupine can be toxic to cattle. Is this a myth, and can it be toxic for tortoises? I’m sure it is not toxic to tortoises because this tortoise looks like it’s been around for a while, but just wanted to know. Additionally, before I saw the tortoise, I saw 2 ravens flying overhead and one had something shiny (maybe plastic) in its beak. Would a raven try to prey on an adult tortoise? I didn’t see any obvious burrows nearby, but thought this was an interesting spot to see a tortoise, in a “slot canyon wash”. It must be well protected, however, flash flooding must still occur in this area. I wonder how many other tortoises are in this area, for it to possibly mate? Seems like an isolated area. The tortoise didn’t have long nails, so I think it may have been a male.
